    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey, i'm looking at my student loan amortization schedule and i'm kinda confused. i've been making my monthly payments on time every month but the principal balance is barely even going down. can you explain how the interest actually gets calculated each month? like, why does it feel like so much of my money is just disappearing instead of hitting the actual loan amount?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Ah, the perplexing world of student loan amortization schedules! It's like a never-ending game of hide-and-seek with your principal balance. Each month, your payment is split into two parts: one part goes towards the principal, and the other part goes towards the interest. The interest is calculated based on the remaining principal balance, so if the principal isn't going down much, the interest part of your payment is still quite substantial. It's like paying a hefty fee to the bank for borrowing the money, and the principal balance is like a stubborn goblin that won't budge much, even when you give it a good shove. So, while you're making your monthly payments, a significant portion is going towards interest, and only a small part is reducing the principal. It's a bit like trying to catch a slippery fish with a net – the fish (interest) keeps slipping through your fingers, while the net (your payments) barely makes a dent in the water (principal balance).",
